<statement>
<p>Solve this system of equations using elimination.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{5}{x}-{6}{y}=-{3}</m> </p>
<p>
  <m>\displaystyle{6}{x}+{6}{y}={0}</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="8"/></p>

</statement>
<solution>
<p><ul><li><m>\displaystyle{\left(-{3},{3}\right)}</m></li></ul></p><p>We chose (for no special reason) to use the first equation to eliminate x from the second equation.</p>
<p>To eliminate we need the scaled version of equation one to have a coefficient of -6. So we scale by <m>\displaystyle-\frac{{6}}{{-{{5}}}}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-\frac{{{6}}}{{-{{5}}}}{\left(-{5}{x}+-{6}{y}\right)}=-\frac{{{6}}}{{-{{5}}}}{\left(-{3}\right)}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{\left({6}\right)}{x}+-{7.2}{y}=-{3.6}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{6}{x}+{6}{y}={0}</m></p>
<p>Adding these two equations gives us</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{1.2}{y}=-{3.6}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{y}=-\frac{{3.6}}{{-{{1.2}}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{y}={3}</m></p>
<p>Finally we can substitute this y value into the first equation to solve for x.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{5}{x}+-{6}{\left({3}\right)}=-{3}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{5}{x}+{\left(-{18}\right)}=-{3}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{5}{x}=-{3}-{\left(-{18}\right)}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{5}{x}={15}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{x}=\frac{{15}}{{-{{5}}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{x}=-{3}</m></p>
<p>Thus the answer is <m>\displaystyle{\left(-{3},{3}\right)}</m>.</p>

</solution>
</myopenmath>